                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d748">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A Combat Areas/6: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-11-08T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 8, 1939—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 8—11 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>190. Local agent of the McCormack Line asks if it is possible under the
                    Neutrality Act that its vessels which call only at Scandinavian ports could
                    proceed from the United States direct to Bergen or north of Bergen, thence to
                    Bergen, Oslo, Goteborg, Copenhagen and Malmo, remaining entirely in neutral
                    territorial waters. Agent points out 20 years establishment of his line to
                    Scandinavia and great loss if forced to abandon. I gave him no encouragement but
                    said I would transmit inquiry. He states steamship <hi rend="italic"
                        >Mormactide</hi> is scheduled to sail next Friday from New York.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
